29/06/2004
BELGRADE, Serbia-Montenegro -- The EU and the United States were among the first to congratulate Boris Tadic's victory in Serbia's presidential election, hailing his record of democratic reform.
Croatia too welcomed the victory, saying on Monday (28 June) that it marks Serbia's departure from the legacy of Slobodan Milosevic and his authoritarian regime.
In an interview with CNN, Tadic said that his was a victory against the past.
He beat Tomislav Nikolic of the Serbian Radical Party in Sunday's run-off.
In other news Monday, Milorad "Legija" Lukovic pleaded not guilty to charges he kidnapped and murdered former Serbian President Ivan Stambolic in August 2000.The former police special operations commander is also accused of murdering Prime Minister Zoran Djindjic in March 2003.
(B92, Tanjug, Beta, FoNet, BBC, AFP - 28/06/04)
